[size=2][i]Nexus description in BBCode. Set the mission patch (branding/osf-ui-patch.png) as the mod's
main/thumbnail image in the Nexus UI. Upload branding/osf-ui-header.png (the banner below), the
section-headers/*.png, and your in-game screenshots to the mod's image gallery, then paste each one's
Nexus-hosted URL into the [img] tags below (the file paths here are placeholders — Nexus only renders
images it hosts).[/i][/size]

[center][img]REPLACE-WITH-NEXUS-URL/osf-ui-header.png[/img][/center]

[center][size=5][b]Modern web UI, rendered over Starfield.[/b][/size][/center]

[center][i]OSF UI is a framework, not a UI mod. On its own it provides the built-in Control Deck for framework settings and registered mods.[/i][/center]

[line]

[center][img]REPLACE-WITH-NEXUS-URL/01-overview.png[/img][/center]
OSF UI is an SFSE plugin that lets mods build interfaces in [b]HTML, CSS and JavaScript[/b] and draws them over the live game. Pages render offscreen through [b]Ultralight[/b] (the same WebKit-based engine behind Prisma UI on Skyrim), upload to a GPU texture on Starfield's own Direct3D 12 device, and are composited as an alpha-blended overlay at present time — so a view is just a web page, authored with tools you already know.

It is [b]content-neutral[/b]. The engine ships the [i]mechanisms[/i] (rendering, input capture, the hardware cursor, the native↔web bridge, a schema-driven settings system); the actual interfaces live in the mods built on top of it. Out of the box it ships one thing to look at: an MCM-style [b]settings panel[/b].

[center][img]REPLACE-WITH-NEXUS-URL/02-features.png[/img][/center]
[list]
[*][b]Real web pages over the game[/b] — HTML/CSS/JS views rendered by Ultralight, composited on the game's own D3D12 device (no separate window, no injected renderer)
[*][b]Fully interactive[/b] — while a view is open the game is input-frozen (movement, camera, and gamepad), keyboard routes into the page, and the real Windows [b]hardware cursor[/b] clicks its controls — zero-lag and framerate-independent, with CSS [font=Courier New]cursor[/font] styles mapped to the matching system cursor
[*][b]Multi-view compositing[/b] — several views layer together by z-order; [font=Courier New]Tab[/font] cycles focus between the interactive ones
[*][b]Schema-driven settings (MCM-style)[/b] — each mod drops a small JSON schema of typed knobs (bool / int / float / enum / string) and gets a card with live controls, clamping, Reset, and per-mod persistence — no UI code required
[*][b]A native↔web bridge[/b] — a whitelisted JSON message API ([font=Courier New]window.osfui[/font]) for surface control, diagnostics, read-only game data, and settings; trusted native SFSE plugins can register their own commands
[*][b]Safe by construction[/b] — page JS is untrusted: the view filesystem is sandboxed to its own folder and network access is force-disabled
[/list]

[center][img]REPLACE-WITH-NEXUS-URL/03-get-started.png[/img][/center]
[size=4][b]Requirements[/b][/size]
[list]
[*][url=https://www.nexusmods.com/starfield/mods/106]SFSE[/url] matching your game version
[*][url=https://www.nexusmods.com/starfield/mods/3256]Address Library for SFSE Plugins[/url]
[/list]

[size=4][b]Installation[/b][/size]
Install with a mod manager (Mod Organizer 2 / Vortex) and enable it — the archive drops straight into [font=Courier New]Data\SFSE\Plugins[/font]. Requires SFSE + Address Library.

[size=4][b]Try it (5 seconds)[/b][/size]
Launch the game through SFSE and press [b]F10[/b]. The Mods control deck opens, the game freezes, and the mouse cursor clicks its controls. Press [b]F10[/b] again (or [b]Esc[/b]) to close.

[center][img]REPLACE-WITH-NEXUS-URL/04-for-authors.png[/img][/center]
Building a UI on OSF UI is web development.
[list]
[*][b]Declarative path:[/b] ship a [font=Courier New]views/<id>/[/font] folder (manifest + [font=Courier New]index.html[/font] / [font=Courier New]style.css[/font] / [font=Courier New]main.js[/font]) and, for settings, a [font=Courier New]settings/<id>.json[/font] schema. No C++, no Papyrus.
[*][b]Native path:[/b] a separate SFSE plugin can register its own bridge commands and drive views through the exported [font=Courier New]OSFUI_RequestBridge[/font] API.
[/list]
[i]Note: this is a young framework — the [font=Courier New]window.osfui[/font] bridge is 0.x and still changing.[/i] Full docs — authoring views, the bridge protocol, and the settings schema — are on [url=https://github.com/ozooma10/osf-ui]GitHub[/url].

[center][img]REPLACE-WITH-NEXUS-URL/05-credits.png[/img][/center]
[size=4][b]Compatibility &amp; content policy[/b][/size]
[list]
[*][b]SFW.[/b] The framework is content-neutral and contains no adult assets.
[*][b]Steam only.[/b] SFSE is Steam-only, so OSF UI does not work on Xbox / Game Pass.
[*]Coexistence with ReShade / the Steam overlay / frame-generation is untested; HDR / 10-bit backbuffers are detected and skipped (with a log line) rather than rendered.
[*]Reverse-engineered against the current Starfield + SFSE; a runtime layout guard refuses UI integration rather than crashing if the engine layout doesn't match.
[/list]

[size=4][b]Source, permissions &amp; license[/b][/size]
OSF UI is [b]open source[/b] (GPL-3.0 with a modding/linking exception that permits shipping the proprietary Ultralight runtime). Full source, build instructions, and issue tracker: [url=https://github.com/ozooma10/osf-ui]github.com/ozooma10/osf-ui[/url]. Bug reports and pull requests welcome.

[size=4][b]Credits[/b][/size]
OSF UI exists because of [b]Prisma UI[/b] by [b]StarkMP[/b] — the Skyrim framework that pioneered rendering modern HTML/CSS/JS interfaces over a Bethesda game with Ultralight. The entire idea came from Prisma UI, and StarkMP kindly gave permission to build a Starfield-flavored framework in its spirit. OSF UI is an independent, from-scratch implementation for Starfield with its own name, architecture, and API; it is [b]not affiliated with or endorsed by Prisma UI, and contains no Prisma UI code.[/b]
[list]
[*][b]StarkMP[/b] (with contributors incl. [b]langfod[/b]) — [url=https://www.nexusmods.com/skyrimspecialedition/mods/148718]Prisma UI[/url] — original concept and inspiration
[*][b][url=https://ultralig.ht/]Ultralight[/url][/b] (Ultralight, Inc.) — the WebKit-based renderer behind every view (used under the Ultralight Free License; notices ship in [font=Courier New]OSFUI/ultralight/license/[/font])
[*][b]CommonLibSF[/b] / [url=https://github.com/libxse/commonlibsf-template]commonlibsf-template[/url] &amp; [url=https://sfse.silverlock.org/]SFSE[/url] — the plugin foundation this is built on
[/list]
Full attributions and licenses are in CREDITS.md and THIRD_PARTY notices in the repository.
